  <description><![CDATA[<p>Ski Megeve! Just over an hour from Geneva, the chic, traditional resort of Megève - a truly iconic resort long before the advent of France’s better known purpose-built ski stations -  does good business in summer as well as winter. For this reason it has a unique ambience, with its open air ice rink, horse-drawn sleighs and cobbled streets, complete with a pedestrian zone which features a fine medieval church. The ski area, much of it below the treeline , includes the main Rochebrune area, Mont d’Arbois and Jaillet.  We offer accommodation in three villages, all of which access this impressive ski area with miles of blue and red runs, some unexpectedly good off-piste and some fantastic mountain restaurants. Apart from Megève, the Evasion Mont Blanc ski areas covers a massive 325m of trails, split between a number of areas including St-Gervais and Les Contamines.  The Jaillet sector links with with Comploux and La Giettaz. </p>
<!-- <p><strong>St Gervais</strong></p>
<p>This is a fascinating cosmopolitan ski-area-cum-spa-town set snugly in a narrow river gorge between Megève and Chamonix. Unlike some modern-day French resorts, St Gervais has some really attractive traditional architecture, interesting shops, bars and restaurants, a market and casino. It also has its own mainline railway station, with links to Geneva and Martigny, and a chance to ride the spectacular Mont Blanc Tramway,  France’s highest mountain rack railway<b>. </b>A gondola link to Mont d’Arbois enables<b> </b>St Gervais to share neighbouring Megève’s extensive slopes (which has some great off-piste if you know where to look – or even better, hire a guide!) as well as the other four ski areas in the Evasion Mont Blanc network: 325km of pistes served by 116 lifts (one of the largest in France). Although the Rochebrune is exclusive to Megève, the Jaillet area is shared with Comploux and La Giettaz, the newest sector of Megève with some good steep slopes and wonderful views. It also shares stunning close-up views of the Mont Blanc massif,  and has some good runs of its own. </p> -->]]></description>
